3. Resampling technique¶

The Poland bankruptcy dataset is a binary classification problem where the positive class (bankruptcy) is severely under-represented, making it a heavily imbalanced dataset. In such cases, RandomOverSampler can be a good option as it is a simple technique that can effectively balance the dataset by randomly duplicating the minority class samples until a balanced class distribution is achieved.

To address class imbalance, we used the RandomOverSampler resampling technique using the sampling_strategy = 'minority' parameter to help correct imbalance.This randomly oversamples the minority class to balance the dataset. We chose this technique because it does not discard any data and can increase the overall performance of the model.

It is important to notice that resampleing must occur after the splitting of data in a training and testing set. This is because if resampling is done on the entire data set then data leakage will occur and essentially heavily overfit your model causing results such as 100% on all scores¶

Create RandomOverSampler object

In [20]:
from imblearn.over_sampling import RandomOverSampler
ros = RandomOverSampler(random_state=42, sampling_strategy = 'minority')

Resample the data

In [21]:

The confusion matrix above shows that there were a total of 1996 predictions made. Out of those, 1905 were true negative predictions (i.e., the model correctly identified negative cases), and 30 were true positive predictions (i.e., the model correctly identified positive cases). However, the model also made 53 false negative predictions (i.e., the model predicted negative, but the actual value was positive) and 8 false positive predictions (i.e., the model predicted positive, but the actual value was negative).

In this case, the model has a high number of true negatives, indicating that it is good at identifying negative cases. However, it has a relatively low number of true positives, suggesting that it struggles to correctly identify positive cases. The number of false negatives is also notable, indicating that the model is failing to identify some positive cases.

Due to the high imbalance even after resampling this can not be helped without changing the training data

7. Reporting (10 marks)¶

Loading data¶

We loaded the data from poland-bankruptcy-data-2009 by unzipping the zipped file with gzip library, then converting the json file type to a dataframe with pd.DataFrame which is from pandas library.

Preparing data¶

We checked for null values and replaced with the mean using SimpleImputer. We chose to replace the nulls with the mean as removing Nulls caused a increase in the imbalance of the dataset as the amount of true values fro the entire dataset went from 4% to 1% and false values from 96% to 99%. We used a heat map matrix to view the Correlation between features and target column and determined that there was a low or negative correlation with all features.

Train-test split And Resampling technique¶

We then split the data and resampled the training dataset. The Poland bankruptcy dataset is a binary classification problem where the positive class (bankruptcy) is severely under-represented, making it a heavily imbalanced dataset. In such cases, RandomOverSampler can be a good option as it is a simple technique that can effectively balance the dataset by randomly duplicating the minority class samples until a balanced class distribution is achieved. In this project, we worked with bankruptcy data for companies in Poland, using the GradientBoosting classification algorithm to predict whether a company will go bankrupt or not. To address class imbalance, we used the RandomOverSampler resampling technique using the sampling_strategy = 'minority' parameter to help correct imbalance. This randomly oversamples the minority class to balance the dataset. We chose this technique because it does not discard any data and can.

By resampling the entire data set we achieve 100% Accuracy and Precision with the test data set but resampling the entire data set this cause data leakage and inaccurate scores. We therefore resampled only the trainning data which caused a decrease in metrics due to the high imbalanced nature of the data set even after resampling.

Models¶

We first trained a standard grained boost model, then with a Hyperparameter tuning version and a top 10 version to be able to compare the results. Interestingly enough we found that the top ten model has the same results as the tuned Gradient-Boosting model which means the top ten features are a good representation of the overall features of the model.

Hyperparameter tuning¶

We used GridSearchCV to perform hyperparameter tuning for the GradientBoostingClassifier algorithm, and found that the optimal parameters were: (max_depth=12, max_features=1.0, min_samples_leaf=5, min_samples_split=3, n_estimators=200)

learning_rate: The learning rate shrinks the contribution of each tree by a factor of learning_rate in order to reduce overfitting.

n_estimators: The number of boosting stages to perform. This corresponds to the number of trees in the model.

max_depth: The maximum depth of each decision tree in the ensemble. The higher the max_depth the more complex the model which in return increases over-fitting.

min_samples_split: The minimum number of samples required to split an internal node. This helps to avoid overfitting by requiring a minimum number of samples to be present in a node before it can be split.

min_samples_leaf: The minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node. A leaf node is a node without any children. This helps to avoid overfitting by requiring a minimum number of samples to be present at the end of a branch.

max_features: The number of features to consider when looking for the best split.

The model achieved an accuracy of 0.97 , precision of 0.79 , recall of 0.36, and an F1-score of 0.5 on the testing set.

Feature importance and Feature importance analysis¶

We then determined the top 10 features and trained the model with the hyperparameters and top 10 features.

We also computed the feature importance of the model, and found that the top 10 most important features were:

(feat_34, feat_27, feat_24, feat_26, feat_21, feat_58, feat_46, feat_5, feat_38, feat_39)

Based on the determined features and what they are defined as on the http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/polish+companies+bankruptcy+data website we determined that:

feat_34: The ratio of operating expenses to total liabilities is an important indicator. Higher values of this feature suggest higher operating expenses relative to the company's total liabilities.

feat_27: The ratio of profit on operating activities to financial expenses is an important factor. It indicates the profitability of the company's core operations relative to its financial expenses.

feat_24: The ratio of gross profit over a period of three years to total assets is a significant measure. It provides insights into the company's long-term profitability in relation to its total assets.

feat_26: The ratio of net profit plus depreciation to total liabilities is a crucial metric. It reflects the company's financial stability by considering its net profit and depreciation relative to its total liabilities.

feat_21: The sales growth rate is an important feature. It compares the current period's sales to the sales of the previous period, indicating the company's performance in terms of revenue growth.

feat_58: The ratio of total costs to total sales is an insightful measure. It indicates the efficiency of cost management in relation to the company's revenue generation.

feat_46: The ratio of current assets minus inventory to short-term liabilities is a significant indicator. It reflects the company's ability to cover its short-term obligations using its current assets excluding inventory.

feat_5: This feature represents a complex calculation involving cash, short-term securities, receivables, short-term liabilities, operating expenses, and depreciation. It provides insights into the company's cash flow management and profitability over a year.

feat_38: The ratio of constant capital to total assets is an important measure. It assesses the company's financial structure by considering its constant capital (a long-term funding source) relative to its total assets.

feat_39: The ratio of profit on sales to sales is a significant performance indicator. It measures the company's profitability per unit of sales and highlights its ability to generate profits from its revenue.

Overall, the feature importance analysis helps us understand the most important financial indicators that impact a company's likelihood of bankruptcy. By paying close attention to these indicators, companies can better manage their financial health and reduce their risk of bankruptcy.

Comparing the models, we can observe the following:

The initial Gradient Boost model had a higher number of true positives (60), but it also had a higher number of false positives (155) compared to the other two models. This indicates that it was more likely to incorrectly predict positive cases.

After tuning the Gradient Boost model, the number of true positives decreased to 30, while the number of false positives decreased to 8. This suggests that the model became more conservative in predicting positive cases, resulting in a lower number of false positives.

The Top-10 Gradient Tuned model shows the same performance as the tuned Gradient Boost model, with 30 true positives and 8 false positives.

Overall, the tuned models (Gradient Boost Tuned and Top-10 Gradient Tuned) show improved performance compared to the initial Gradient Boost model in terms of reducing false positives. This suggests that the tuning process helped the model make more accurate predictions in identifying positive cases.

Model Accuracy Precision Recall F1 score ROC AUC score
0 Gradient boost 0.91 0.28 0.72 0.4 0.82
1 Tunned Gradient boost 0.97 0.79 0.36 0.5 0.68
2 Tunned Gradient boost with top 10 0.97 0.79 0.36 0.5 0.68

Accuracy: It represents the overall correctness of the model's predictions. Higher accuracy indicates a higher proportion of correct predictions.

Precision: It measures the proportion of correctly predicted positive instances out of the total predicted positive instances. A higher precision means a lower rate of false positives.

Recall: It measures the proportion of correctly predicted positive instances out of the actual positive instances. A higher recall means a lower rate of false negatives.

F1 Score: It is the harmonic mean of precision and recall and provides a single metric to evaluate the model's performance, considering both precision and recall.

ROC AUC Score: It measures the model's ability to distinguish between positive and negative classes, where a higher score indicates better performance.

Tunned Gradient boost Model and Tunned Gradient boost with top 10 Model have higher accuracy, precision, and F1 score compared to standard Gradient boost Model. However, the recall for all three models is relatively low, indicating a higher rate of false negatives. We can see that selecting the top 10 values did not have a impact on the metrics which means the top 10 features are the most important while the others are not needed.
